body:
Thanks for the reply @omalleyt12 .
Note that I am working on Windows, not Linux. 
I did. Using Tensorflow version 1.10.0 and my callback is: 

```
callbacks = [
        # Write TensorBoard logs to `./logs` directory
        tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard() ]

history = model.fit([X_train_seqs, masked_X_train_seqs], y=tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(YDocLevel_train, 13),
              validation_data=([X_valid_seqs, masked_X_valid_seqs], tf.keras.utils.to_categorical(YDocLevel_valid, 13)),
              batch_size=16, epochs=100, shuffle=True, callbacks= callbacks)
```

still got the same error:
File "D:\Anaconda2\envs\tensorflow\lib\site-packages\tensorflow\python\keras\callbacks.py", line 71, in set_model
    callback.set_model(model)
  File "D:\Anaconda2\envs\tensorflow\lib\site-packages\tensorflow\python\keras\callbacks.py", line 782, in set_model
    self.merged = tf_summary.merge_all()
  File "D:\Anaconda2\envs\tensorflow\lib\site-packages\tensorflow\python\summary\summary.py", line 311, in merge_all
    'Merging tf.summary.* ops is not compatible with eager execution. '
RuntimeError: Merging tf.summary.* ops is not compatible with eager execution. Use tf.contrib.summary instead.
